quote: Absolutely. We'll celebrate after you've settled in.
Great.
I can carry that.
I've got it.
Well. If you'll excuse me...
Did I do something wrong?
... and Julian and Miles have become even more obsessed with their Alamo program if you can believe it. I half expect Miles to start wearing a coonskin cap to work.
You see... Davy Crockett wore this cap made of... a raccoonskin and...
I know the program.
Oh. Well, I think we've covered just about everything you missed while you were away.
Is there anything you want to talk about?
Not particularly.
Here it comes...
What?

The "cane problem." You're about to ask me why I need to walk with the cane since Doctor Benbasset told you my biosynthetic leg is working perfectly. He also told you the problem's all in my head. That I'm crazy.
He didn't say that.
It's what he thinks.
Forget what he thinks. What do you think? Why do you need the cane?
My leg hurts. And if I put my full weight on it, it hurts more. So I have to limp. And that means I need to walk with a cane.
Sounds reasonable to me.

Good. Look -- can I be perfectly honest with you? I've spent the last three weeks talking about my feelings with the counselors on Starbase Two- Three-Five... and to tell you the truth, I'm a little sick of it. I just want to be left alone for a while.
I understand. I think we've done enough for today. I'll see you tomorrow.
Computer -- what time is it?
The time is eleven thirty-two hours.
Jake says he's sleeping over eighteen hours a day and Julian says he's missed his last two physical therapy appointments.
And his counseling sessions are going nowhere -- in his words, he's "sick of talking about his feelings." Can't say I blame him. He's been under constant psychiatric care for almost two months now.
So what do we do?
I'm not sure. For now, our best option may be to simply watch and wait.
Not my first choice.
I know. But sometimes a patient can help guide his own treatment. Let's see what Nog does next.
Nog, I want to be understanding and I want to be your friend, but enough is enough. You've been playing that same stupid song for three days. I can't take it anymore.
Aren't you going to say anything? You've barely said three words to me since you came home.
Maybe I don't have anything to say.
I'm trying to help you here, Nog, but you're not making it easy.
You want to help me? Fine. Leave me alone.
All right. But if you want to hear that song again, go rent a holosuite.
... so in order to salvage the femoral motor nerves... I'm afraid I have to amputate your leg just above the knee. I'm sorry, but there's no other choice.
Program is running. You may enter when ready.
Hi there, pallie. Vic Fontaine.
I know. I'm Nog.
You're Rom's kid, right?
Right.
He's really proud of you -- he's always in here bragging about his son, the soldier boy.
Yeah.
What can I do for you?
I want to hear, "I'll Be Seeing You."
Sure thing, kiddo. Any other requests?
No. Just "I'll Be Seeing You."
Sounds like it's a special tune.
It is. It helped me out once when I was... unhappy.
What more can you ask from a song?
Doctor?
Yes?
What is that?
It's a song I had Vic Fontaine record for me.
Vic... ?
He's a character in a holosuite program of mine. I thought it might take our minds off our troubles. Is it bothering you?
No. It's kind of nice...
Thank you. Take five, fellas.
That's it, kid. I know fifteen different arrangements of that tune and you've heard 'em all. So, which one's your favorite?
The first.
Somehow, I knew you were going to say that.
So let me guess -- Julian played it for you, right?
Right.
If I had him as a publicist I'd be bigger than Elvis.
Who?
Never mind. So how's the new leg?
You know about that?
People talk.
If you really want to know... it hurts.
Can they give you something for that?

No, they say it's all in my head. "According to my tricorder, the pain receptors in your leg aren't being stimulated, Nog. You must be imagining it." But I don't care what they say, it hurts all the time.
I believe you.
You're the only one.
So what else can I do for you? Sing it again?
Good. To tell you the truth, I was starting to get a little sick of it myself. How 'bout something else?
No... all I want to do is go to bed.
Okay. I'll catch you later.
Yeah.
Something wrong?
I don't want to go back to my quarters... Actually, I don't want to go back to my life...
Where do you live -- in this program, I mean. Do you have a... house or... ?
I have a suite here in the hotel.
Do you have an extra room?
Sure. You want to stay with me tonight?
Maybe more than just tonight. Officially, I'm on medical leave, and according to regulations I can choose my own rehabilitation facility.
You want to choose a holosuite program for your rehab?
Why not?
Okay, kid. If that's the way you want it. From now on, you're staying with me.
Great.
Crazy.
My son is insane.
Rom...
He's a one-legged crazy man!
He's not crazy.
But he is living in a holosuite.
At first, it struck me as a little... peculiar. But after I thought it over, I began to think that maybe this is a good sign after all.
How can hiding in one of Julian's adolescent programs be a good sign?
Hey...
It could be worse. He could be hiding in the Alamo program.
Or that ridiculous secret agent program.
Hey.
Or that stupid Viking program.
Hey!
All right. Are you sure this is in Nog's best interest?
No, I'm not sure. But I think Nog might be subconsciously seeking out his own form of therapy.
I'm sorry, but moving into a holosuite is not my idea of therapy.
Okay, it sounds a little odd.
It sounds ridiculous.
Not really. I'm with Ezri on this one. The mind has a strong natural instinct for survival. For whatever reason, Nog's mind has found shelter in the world of Vic Fontaine.
I think we should wait and let this play itself out.
Well, then someone should talk with Vic -- make him aware of Nog's emotional and physical condition.
I'll do it.
And who's going to pay for all this holosuite time?
I guess I am.
And it's very generous of you. (stands, then to Ezri) Keep me informed.
I get it. He's got some healing to do. I could see that the moment he walked in here.
Great. Any questions?
You sure he doesn't need the cane? Because he's pretty sure he does.
I'm positive. It's a psychological need, not a physical one.
Well, in that case, I've got some ideas on how to wean him off the stick.
Okay, but don't push it.
Hey -- do I seem pushy to you?
No. Well, you know where to reach me if you have any problems.
I got your number.
Hey, kid.
Hey, Vic. Have you seen this movie?
Oh, yeah.
I've heard about you.
What have you heard, Shane?
I've heard that you're a low down Yankee liar.
From these books I can't tell if I'm rich as Rockefeller or poor as a churchmouse.
It's not real money, Vic. Don't worry about it.
Hey, it's real to me, kid.
I could have the computer put some money in your account.
No, thanks. I'll figure it out.
I gotta be going on.
Why, Shane?
Didn't he just get shot a minute ago?
Yeah. He took one in the arm.
But he's not bleeding. He's not even in pain!
Noggles, take it easy -- it's only a movie.
Shane! Come back!
I liked The Searchers better.
Who doesn't? Sonuvagun! I gotta get ready for the show.
The show? I thought we were hanging in.
Hanging out. And we are, but I have a gig to do.
Cancel it.
I can't do that.
Why not?
It would be unprofessional. Besides, performing is my life. It's what I do. I gotta get out there and swing or I'm just another clyde in a tux. You coming to the show?
Sure.
Then may I suggest you carry something with a little more style...
Now this is a cane.
It's a replica of the one Errol Flynn used to have. Except his was a little taller.
It's beautiful... reminds me of the Grand Nagus's staff.
And it has a little secret -- press that button on the back of the head.
It's great. But what's it for?
You never know when a lady might need a light. Now be careful with that stick, it's a little fragile -- I don't think it'll take your whole weight.
Actually, I don't need to put my whole weight on it.
Good. Now we better get dressed.
Tuxedoes?
Hey -- you're catching on.
Hi there.
Nog, let me introduce you to --
Down in front!
Sorry.
Nog, this is Kesha. Kesha -- Nog.
Nice to meet you.
Welcome to Las Vegas.
Thanks.
Thank you, you're too kind. I guess that's the response you get when you pack the house with relatives.
So what've you been doing?
Hanging out.
Out of what?
It's an expression.
There's a lot of old Earth slang in this program. Right, Daddy-O?
Right.
Why don't I get us some drinks? Kesha, what'll you have?
Makara fizz.
They don't serve that here.
Oh. Well, what're you having?
A martini. Two olives.
I'll have the same.
Be right back.
Jake says you're going to be the first Ferengi captain in Starfleet.
We'll see.
He also says you're quite a hero.
I'm not a hero.
Don't be so modest. Jake's not the only one. Everyone on the station says that --
I said, I'm not a hero. Okay?
Okay.
Which one?
What?
That's what you're wondering right? Which leg is it?
I -- I wasn't wondering about... that...
About what?
About your... you know...
My new leg? Can't you say it?
No -- yes. I mean, I'm not trying to say anything...
Then maybe you should just keep quiet.
Here we go -- three martinis.
I think we should go, Jake.
That sounds like a good idea.
Uh... what's going on?
It's all my fault. I didn't mean to stare...
At what?
What do you think?
Oh...
I'm really sorry if I made you uncomfortable.
Wonderful. Good-bye.
Hold on. She said she was sorry.
I heard her. Now you can go.
What's wrong with you?
I said get out.
Nog...
Let me put it another way...
You okay?
Yeah... I'm fine.
And you... take a hike.
What?
You heard me. You don't come into my club and start hitting customers. Now get out before I throw you out.
Still up?
I couldn't sleep.
You mind... ?
What a night...
I'm sorry about what happened.
Don't apologize to me -- I'm not the one you belted.
I'll settle things with Jake.
And his girl.
Absolutely. Can I go back to the club tomorrow night?
I can't have you hitting the customers. It's bad for business.
I promise it'll never happen again.
Okay. What got into you, anyway?
I don't know. She started calling me a hero and things kind of went downhill from there.
She called you a hero? And for that you slug your best friend? Remind me not to pay you any compliments.
I am beat. That's never happened before.
What?
Me getting tired. My program's never run this long. Usually people come in, they ask for a song or two... sometimes a night on the town... but I've never had to put in a full day.
Maybe you should go to bed.
I got work to do. If I don't get those books in order, Uncle Sam is going to come down on me like a ton of bricks.
Sounds like my uncle. Is there anything I can do?
You know anything about bookkeeping?
I'm a Ferengi. It's in our blood.
They're all yours.
Where's your computer?
Right here. It's nineteen sixty-two. What do you want from me?
It's all right. I can do it this way.
Well, I'm going to hit the sack.
Vic, can I ask you a question?
Sure.
When you sleep... do you dream?
Good-night, kid.
Good-night.

... but this time he's switched all the robes in the steam room. So when Dino goes to pick up his robe, he doesn't realize that across the back, Frank has written, in big bold letters-- (catches sight of Ezri) I'll finish the story later.
Hi, dollface.
Hi. Where's Nog?
Up in the room. He's still working on the receipts from sixty-one. That's kid's a hell of an accountant. He says the government owes me money -- can you believe that?
I need to talk to him.
Can it wait?
I'm afraid not.
This is about the thing with Jake, right? Is he pressing charges?
No. But I think it's time for Nog to leave the holosuite.
Wait a minute. He likes it here. He's making real progress. Okay, he lost his cool, but I don't think it'll happen again.
Vic, he can't hide in here forever. He has to face reality sometime.
The kid's had too much reality lately, if you ask me. He's lost a leg, he's watched good friends die. Like you told me, we shouldn't push him -- he needs time to heal.
No offense, but you're just a hologram. I'm his counselor. I outrank you... or something. And I think it's time for him to go.
He's on medical leave. And according to Starfleet regulations, he can spend it anywhere he chooses.
How do you know that?
I told him.
And if you try to force me to leave I'll resign my commission.
Wait a minute... let's slow down here. No one's talking about forcing anyone to do anything.
Good. Because Vic and I have big plans.
We do?
I've been going over your books. This place is a latinum-mine and you don't even know it. In my opinion, it's time to expand the business.
Nog, this is a holosuite.
Of course it's a holosuite. But that doesn't mean we can't build a new casino.
A new casino? (takes the adding machine tape) How much money do I have?
If you'll excuse us, counselor, we have business to conduct...
Go easy on the garnishes. People order a drink, they don't want a fruit bowl in their glass.
We'll talk about this later.
I'll take care of them.
Hey -- long time, no see.
Hi.
Oh, Nog!
Right this way...
So... how are you?
Couldn't be better. Business is booming. We're making money hand over fist. I can barely keep up with all the profits.
Those are... holographic profits, right?
Uh... yeah. So what's new with you?
Rom got a promotion.
Maintenance engineer first class.
That's great! Congratulations!
Thanks.
We should celebrate. We could close the lounge, have a private party...
Actually, Chief O'Brien threw him a party last night.
Oh.
It was a spur of the moment thing... no invitations or anything...
Don't worry about it. I probably couldn't have gotten away -- last night was really busy...
Uh-oh. A big player just walked in. Excuse me for a minute -- I have to go schmooze.
Okay. See you later.
'Bye.
I hope you're still talking to me...
Of course I am.
I've got to hand it to you, Vic, you've done a great job with him. He seems like a new man.
He just needed a little time, that's all.
... heals all wounds, right?
Giving him that cane was a great idea. I haven't seen him limp in days.
It gets better. Yesterday, we drove out to see the architect who's designing the casino, and I saw him actually run up a flight of stairs.
No kidding.
Would I kid a kidder?
So what's next for you two?

Well, we don't break ground on the casino for another week, so I thought we could fly up to Tahoe for a couple of days. Sammy's going to be performing at the Cal- Neva and I thought I'd introduce the kid to him.
Sammy's a friend of yours... ?
We're tight.
I see. So you're going to have Sammy convince him it's time to leave the holosuite?
Well... no.

Forget it. I should know better by now than to ask you to give away your secrets. You probably have everything all mapped out. I mean, what am I thinking? That this "new casino" is anything more than a ploy? That you're really going to let him live out the rest of his life in a holosuite?
No... no, of course not. The casino's just a... a ploy, like you said.
They'll be so happy to have him back.
Yeah...
He is better, isn't he?
It's just like you said -- he needed a break from reality. Now all that's left is to decide when he's ready to go back. But I'll leave that up to you. See you 'round.
See ya.
Great set tonight.
Thanks. Lot of familiar faces in the crowd. Did I see Rom and Leeta out there?
They came for a while.
What do you think about moving the crap tables over to the south wing and expanding the slot machines out into here?
Good idea.
I'll think it over.
But I'm supposed to meet with the architect tomorrow morning.
Not anymore. It's time for you to go, kid.
Go where?
You know where. It's time to end the program.
But... we've got work to do... we have a casino to build.
No we don't. This is just a fantasy... it's not real.
It's real to me and it's real to you -- and don't say it isn't. I know better.
You're right -- it's very real to me. But I'm a hologram, Nog. I'm not a person. Until you came along, I'd never been on for more than six or seven hours straight.
I know! But now you're running all the time. Isn't it great?

It's incredible. Since you've been here, I've slept in a bed every night... gone to work every day... had time to read the paper, play cards with the boys I've had a life. And I have to tell you, it's a precious thing I had no idea how much it means to just... live. Now, I'm going to return the favor and give you your life back.
But I don't want that life anymore, Vic. I'm perfectly happy here.
What "here?" There is no "here." Don't you get it? This is nowhere. It's an illusion. And so am I. In fact, the only thing in this entire program that isn't an illusion is you.
Okay. You're right. But I'm not ready to go back yet. I need more time. So let's just sleep on this and we'll talk about it tomorrow.
Kid... I hate to do this to you, but you're not giving me any choice. Computer --
No, don't!
-- end program.
Oh. Hi, Nog.
Chief. Something wrong?
Uh... no. I was running a diagnostic in Ops and noticed a magnetic flux anomaly in the holosuite transilluminator circuits. Didn't realize it was you.
Sorry. I'm... just having trouble getting the Las Vegas program to run.
You know... Vic's matrix is a little different than your standard photokinetic hologram. He can turn himself off. If he doesn't want to appear... he doesn't.
You mean he has free will?
I'm an engineer, not a philosopher. All I know is that when Vic turns himself off, he's off, and ripping out the guts of the holosuite isn't going to change that.
Is there anything else I can do for you?
No.
We uh... we all miss you in Ops.
Yeah.
... now that the chief's told you I'm smarter than the average bear, will you stop messin' around with my holosuite?
If you'll turn the program back on.
What is it I'm not making clear to you, Charley? You have to go.
You don't get it. I... I can't go out there.
Why not?
I'm... scared. Okay? I'm scared.

When the war started, I wasn't... happy or anything, but I was... eager. I wanted to test myself... I wanted to see if I had what it takes to be a soldier. And I saw a lot of combat... I saw a lot of people get hurt... I saw a lot of people die... but I never thought anything was going to happen to me. Then suddenly Doctor Bashir is telling me he has to cut my leg off. I couldn't believe it. I still can't believe it. If I can get shot... if I can lose a leg... anything could happen to me, Vic. I could die tomorrow. I don't know if I can face that. If I stay here, at least I know what the future's going to be like.
You stay in here, you're going to die. Not all at once, but little by little. Eventually, you'll become as hollow as I am.
You don't seem hollow to me.
Compared to you, I'm hollow as a snare drum.

Kid, I don't know what's going to happen to you out there. All I can tell you is that you've got to play the cards life deals you. Sometimes you win, sometimes you lose... but at least you're in the game.
Crazy.
He seemed happy...
And he's stopped limping...
You're joking.
No. He's a new man. You should go visit.
I don't think I need to...
Hi.
Hi.
Are you okay?
No. But I will be.
Computer -- run program Bashir sixty-two.
Hi, pallie. Nice threads.
Thanks.
You back at work?
Limited duty. Just a couple hours a day.
How's it feel?
Different. I feel... older.
Happens to the best of us.
I wanted to thank you for all you did for me.
That's not necessary. You did something for me too -- you gave me a chance to see what it's like to have a life.
You're going to have that chance again. I've made arrangements with my uncle Quark to keep this program running twenty-six hours a day from now on.
What?
It's my gift to you.
Kid... I don't know what to say.
Just put it there, pallie and tell me you'll always save me a seat up front.
It's a deal. And you can take that to the bank.
Gotta go. I'm buying Jake and Kesha dinner tonight.
Try not to overturn the furniture.
I'll try...
Twenty-six hours a day...
"I've got the world on a string/Sitting on a rainbow/Got the string around my finger/What a world, what a life... "
"I'm in love... "
Heard anything?
Should be here any minute, sir. She's running a little late.
This is no way to start a new relationship...
So... how's Odo?
His body shows no sign of the changeling disease. I believe he's cured.
That's great.
I'll probably release him from the Infirmary this afternoon.
That's really... great.
Yes... it is.
I don't get it. He's interested, she's interested -- what's the problem?
He is an overgrown child and she is... very confused.
It could still work.
She's here.
On screen.
I didn't know we were getting another Defiant-class ship.
That's what happens when you miss staff meetings.
Looks just like her...
Let's hope she fights like her.
Attention to Orders.

quote: Cardassia. It's as beautiful as I remembered.
It won't be beautiful in my eyes until the Dominion's gone.
Orbital traffic control is asking for our security clearance.
I'll handle it.
We're taking a big risk coming here. I hope this is worth it.

Gul Revok and Legate Goris are ready to bring their troops over to our side. That's over half a million men. If we can convince Gul Seltan to join us as well, we'll have another hundred thousand. I'd say that's worth the risk.
And you're sure you want me along?
Before they join us, they'll want assurances that the Federation will support them.
We're cleared for standard orbit.
Do you have the transport coordinates?
Yes. The transporter room is standing by.
Then the bridge is yours, Seskal.
Good luck.
Is that all of them? Yes, sir! Secure the area! Follow me! Inform the First that we have killed the traitors.
How did they know?
Gul Revok. He betrayed us.
Kira to Seskal. Get us out of here.
We're under attack! I can't lower the shields. Lock disruptors and return fire! Transfer auxiliary power to--
Seskal... ? Seskal... ?
Seskal... do you read me... ?
I don't think they're up there anymore.
We have to get out of here. Damar, do you know any place we can go?
Everyone I know on Cardassia has either been arrested or killed.
I might know someone who'll take us in... that is, if we can get to the capital.
Well, we can't stay here.
... I don't hear from you for years, then you show up on my doorstep with these people.
I do apologize for the intrusion, but you're the only person on Cardassia I can trust.
It's smaller than I remembered...
I grew up in this house. Didn't I mention that?
I thought you said Enabran Tain used to live here.
Tain was Garak's father.
He could never acknowledge it publicly because he was the head of the Obsidian Order. Mila was our housekeeper and most trusted confidante.
I was never a very good cook, but I knew how to keep a secret.
We need to contact the other Resistance cells and warn them about Revok. Is there any way you can get us a com-unit?
You shouldn't be involved in this.
We're attempting to free our people. Do you want to live under the Dominion for the rest of your life?
I'm an old woman. I'm long past caring about such things. But I'll get you your com-unit.
Mila... Thank you. I promise we won't be staying long.
At least make yourselves useful. This room hasn't been cleaned in years...
You heard the lady...
Ah, the glamor of being a revolutionary...
Go ahead. What have you got to lose?
Our jobs.
Let's do it. At this point, I don't care if he fires me.
That's the spirit. Remember -- ask for ten percent, but settle for fifteen.
Okay.
Quark... we have something to say.
Then say it.
We don't think we should have to give you twenty percent of our tips.
Uh-huh.
We think ten percent is more than fair and we're not going back to work until this is settled!
Ten percent?
There's an incoming transmission from Ferenginar. It's the Grand Nagus!
Zek? I'll take it in the back. I'll think about it.
What'd he say?
He's going to think about it!
Is that you, ?
It's me.
(peering into the camera) barely see you.
It's the static.
Sorry about the . It's raining here.
It's always raining there.
Not this kind of rain. (There was) an accident at the power plant. The contractor used substandard , the greedy . There's a toxic cloud hanging over the city. What a mess.
So to what do I owe the pleasure... ?
The pressure? That's an ungrateful thing to . I'm not pressuring you.
No. The pleasure.
You're not making any sense. Shut up and listen. I'm retiring.
Your mother and I are moving to Risa to enjoy our old age and -- -- do a lot of , if you know what I mean.
(more than he needs to know) Good for you. I guess.
(holding up his Nagus cane) I'll be coming to Deep Nine to name my successor.
Why here?
Why do think?
To get away from the rain... ?
No, my boy! I've chosen you to succeed me. You're going to be the new Grand Nagus! Congralations, !
Everything checks out fine. I'm certifying you fit for duty.
Finally. The last time I spoke with Kira, she wanted to know when I'd be rejoining her.
Odo, there's something you need to know. When I first discovered that you'd been infected with the morphogenic virus, I assumed you'd contracted it from the Founders.
Didn't I?
No, the fact is... you transmitted the virus to them.
But... how did I get it?
I'm afraid you were infected deliberately.
By whom?
Section Thirty-one.
They used you as a carrier, hoping you'd pass the virus on. You were never meant to develop symptoms, but it appears that a mutation in your --
I don't care whether they meant to kill me or not. The bottom line is the Federation set out to destroy my people.
Thirty-one is not part of the Federation, it's a rogue agency that --
Don't split hairs with me, doctor. They used me as an instrument to try to commit genocide. We may be at war with the Founders, but that's no excuse.
I completely agree.
And what does Starfleet plan to do about it?
The Federation Council considered giving the Founders the cure... but they decided against it.
scene: 26   INT. SISKO'S QUARTERS - CLOSE ON SISKO

quote: Then they're abetting genocide.
scene: 26   INT. SISKO'S QUARTERS - CLOSE ON SISKO

quote: I don't condone what Section Thirty-one did, but the Founders started this war, not us. Giving them the cure would only strengthen their hand. And we can't do that -- not when there are millions of men and women out there putting their lives on the line every day.
scene: 26   INT. SISKO'S QUARTERS - CLOSE ON SISKO

quote: I can see there's no point in arguing with you, the decision's been made.

scene: 26   INT. SISKO'S QUARTERS - CLOSE ON SISKO

quote: Hi.
Hi.
Having lunch?
It's that time.
This is ridiculous.
I know.
You go first.
No, it's all right.
No, I mean it, Julian. You go first.
Okay. You know how much I value our friendship. The thing is that lately... I've been wondering if... maybe we could... be...
Something more?
Yes. Exactly.
I've been wondering the same thing.
I thought it was just me.
Me too.
That's why I've felt so... awkward around you.
I've tried to tell you, but I just... couldn't find the words.
I know. Why is that? I'm not usually like this. If I'm attracted to someone, I let them know. I don't play these ridiculous games.
Neither do I. You know what I think has been holding us back? The friendship.
I was thinking the same thing. We don't want to jeopardize our friendship by trying to turn it into something else.
I've made that mistake before.
So have I. Once you cross that line...
... you can never go back.
And if it doesn't work out, you can never be friends again.
I can't stand the thought of losing you as a friend.
Me, neither.
So. That's that.
We figured it out.
You know, it takes a certain maturity to keep from getting swept up in a romantic fantasy...
To not let a physical attraction override good sense...
Chemistry isn't everything.
Absolutely not. We're adults, after all.
I think we should be proud of ourselves.
Me too. I feel much better.
Friends?
Friends.
Just think. This time next week I'll be living in the Nagal Residence...
They say even the waste extraction fixtures are plated with latinum.
That's right. And the first thing I'm going to do is rip them out and replace them with solid latinum fixtures.
Solid latinum...
That's a little indulgent, don't you think?
Of course, that's the whole point. A Nagus has to lead by example. My greed must be a shining light, a testament to the rewards of avarice.
I hope you're not going to be lonely in that great, big Nagal Residence...
I've got a room picked out for you already, my dear. With a view of the Tower of Commerce.
There'll also be a place for my dear brother, my brave nephew, my lovely sister in-law --
Liquidator Brunt!
Not him.
No, he's here.
What brings you this time, Brunt?
Ferenginar is rife with rumors. They say the Grand Nagus is coming to D.S. Nine to name his successor.
For once, the rumors are right.
I see.
A thousand congratulations, my Nagus!
He's not Nagus yet.
It's never too early to suck up to the boss.
It won't work, Brunt. No amount of groveling can make up for all the trouble you've caused.
Give me a chance.
Grovel some more and I'll think about it.
Oh thank you, your magnificence! I live only to serve at your command!
I think I'm going to like being Nagus. Don't stop.
I am in awe of your splendor! I abase myself before you!
... and thanks to the heroic efforts of Gul Revok, Damar was lured to Cardassia for a meeting with five other traitors.
But his co-conspirators were killed before they could begin plotting against the people of Cardassia.
And Damar himself was killed while trying to penetrate our defense perimeter in a stolen Dominion vessel.
At least they're not looking for us...
I'm also pleased to report that just hours ago, acting on information obtained by our intelligence operatives, our brave troops began a coordinated assault on Damar's terrorist bases.
From Atbar Prime to Regulak Four... from Simperia to Quinor Seven... our forces have eliminated a total of eighteen rebel bases.
All eighteen...
With the rebellion crushed, nothing can impede our march to final victory. Truly, this is a great day for the Dominion.
I don't understand. How could they have compromised our entire organization? We took every precaution... encrypted every transmission... screened every recruit...
It doesn't matter how they did it! It's done! We need to find a way to get off Cardassia.
Garak, can we use this to contact the Federation?
With a signal that strong the Dominion would trace our location within a matter of seconds.
All right. Maybe we could get to a transport
We'd never get past the security checkpoints.
What about Mila? Maybe she knows someone who could help us someone from the Obsidian Order...
I'm afraid Tain and I were her only contacts.
You could at least ask.
I know what the answer will be.
Well, we have to do something! We're not going to sit out the rest of the war in this cellar!
Are we?
Financial advisor? I don't know.
I do have a lot of connections on Ferenginar.
I don't need your connections. As Nagus, people will be lining up to do business with me. You missed a spot.
I'm sure there must be something I can do to change your mind...
Possibly.
Would... forty bricks of gold- pressed latinum do the trick?
No. But seventy would.
Fifty.
Sixty.
Done.
If you'll just sign this...
What is it?
A receipt.
For a bribe?
Surely you're aware of the new regulation making all bribes tax deductible.
Wait, wait, wait. Did you just use... the "T" word?
You mean tax?
Shh! Yeah, that one. Are you telling me there are... T's on Ferenginar?
You haven't been keeping up with the latest reforms, have you? Zek instituted a progressive income tax three months ago.
You call that a reform! T's go against the very spirit of free enterprise -- why do you think they call it free?
The government needed revenue to fund the new social programs -- wage subsidies for the poor, retirement benefits for the aged, health care for --

AHHHH! Stop, stop! No more! I had no idea things had gotten so bad. This is all Moogie's doing. She's been polluting Zek's mind with notions of equality and compassion. Whatever happened to survival of the fittest? Whatever happened to the rich getting richer and the poor getting poorer? Whatever happened to pure, unadulterated greed?
Times change...
And they're going to change back. The first thing I'm going to do is eliminate these so-called reforms, before Ferenginar ends up looking like a... Federation planet.
I'm not sure the Congress of Economic Advisors will approve.
I don't know who they are, and I don't care. As Nagus, I can do whatever I want.
Not... anymore. All regulations proposed by the Nagus must be ratified by the Congress before they become law.
You'll still be a powerful man -- I wouldn't be sucking up to you otherwise.
(calling out to heaven) Oh Blessed Exchequer... forgive us... your children have turned to... democracy.
Did you know you have a hangnail?
If only they could see you now.
Who?
People in the street. Everyone's talking about "Damar and his Rebels."
What are they saying? How stupid we were to walk into a Dominion trap?
How arrogant we were to think we could beat them in the first place?
How glad they are we're dead?
Actually, they don't believe you're dead.
You should hear the stories. "Damar's alive, my cousin saw him on Kelvas Prime." "He faked his own death. He's plotting a new offensive from his secret mountain hideaway."
You didn't tell me you had a secret mountain hideaway.
I thought I'd surprise you.
I wonder why they refuse to believe you're dead?
They're probably so used to being lied to, they don't trust anything the Dominion says.
What if it's more than that... What if we had more of an impact than we realized? What if we've turned you into a legend?
Some legend...

Don't you see? People want to believe in you. We can use that. The organized resistance may be gone, but there's an entire civilian population out there that's fed up with living under the occupation. If Damar -- the man they couldn't kill -- asked the people of Cardassia to stand up against the Dominion...
We might just have a revolution on our hands.
Or you might really get yourselves killed.
Anything's better than rotting in this cellar. How do we begin?
Where's the nearest Jem'Hadar barracks?
Allow me to present Gul -- no, I'm sorry -- Legate Broca, the new head of the Cardassian Union.
I serve the Founders in all things.
Your service is noted.
Thot Pran, I look forward to working with you and the Breen Confederacy.
Your first task will be to give a formal address to the Cardassian people, assuring them that the Dominion has their best interests at --
That can wait.
But it can wait.
We have important matters to discuss. The enemy has devised a countermeasure to our energy- dampening weapon, therefore we must alter our strategy. We're falling back.
No, I don't mean surrender.
Perish the thought. The Dominion hasn't surrendered in battle since it was founded ten thousand years ago.
I'm ordering a strategic retreat of our forces to Cardassian space.
We will establish a new defense perimeter along this line. With less territory to defend, we can concentrate our forces and hold off any attack -- if the enemy attacks at all.
The Federation is by its very nature timid. When they see we've pulled back, their first impulse will be to leave us alone.
What about the Klingons and the Romulans?
I meant no disrespect... I was simply asking --
Without the Federation, the others are no threat to us.

Once we've established the new perimeter, we'll redouble our shipbuilding efforts and increase production of Jem'Hadar troops. Retreat may extend the war by several years, but in the end, we will emerge stronger, and in a far better position to take the Alpha Quadrant once and for all.

-- did you know this Congress of Economic Meddlers actually passed legislation making monopolies illegal? What's the point of being in business if you can't corner the market and gouge your customers?
There's something to be said for keeping prices down by insuring healthy competition. (pressing his own agenda) So what are you going to do with the bar?

(oblivious to Rom's question) You can't even dump industrial waste anymore because it might harm "the natural habitat." I'm supposed to start worrying about animals now? Look how they live -- wallowing in the dirt, sleeping in trees -- that's not natural.
I suppose you could argue that Ferenginar's biodiversity is a precious resource that belongs to everyone. So what are you going to do with the bar?
And don't get me started on this labor-rights thing.
What have we come to when you can't even demand sexual favors from people in your employ?
Unharassed workers are productive workers. So what are you going to do with the bar?
Sell it. What do I want with it, anymore?
(expecting to negotiate) I'll give you five thousand bars of latinum and not a slip more.
That's reasonable.
It is?
(shaking his head sadly) I'm telling you, Rom, our people have lost their way.
(before Quark changes his mind) I just happen to have a contract right here.
I read a report that over forty percent of the population no longer believes that you have to buy your way into the Divine Treasury when you die.
(proffering the PADD) Can I have your thumbprint here, please?
(doing it without even looking) They don't teach children the Rules of Acquisition anymore.
And another print here.
There's a disease spreading through Ferengi society. It's making us soft.
The five thousand has been transferred to your account. It was a pleasure doing business with you.
Five thousand?
I thought you were going to hold me up for at least eight.
I didn't even haggle with you.
I know. It really threw me off.
What's wrong with me... ?
Don't worry, Brother. You're going to be so rich, what's a few thousand bars of latinum?
I've been infected, too. I haven't raised prices in months and I've even been considering letting the dabo girls keep more of their tips! I've gone soft!
I kind of like you better this way.

I don't. And I'm going to do something about it. This disease has got to be stopped before it destroys everything Ferenginar stands for. If Zek wants me to be Nagus, he's going to have to let me do things my way. Or else I'll turn down the job.
Are you serious?
You bet I am.
But being Nagus'll make you rich.
I don't care. I'm not going to preside over the demise of Ferengi civilization. Not me. The line must be drawn here -- this far and no further.
He's been in there too long. Something's wrong.
Let me see your work order.
I showed it to you on the way in.
This has not been approved by the First.
Ah. Yes. Let me explain...
How much time?
The detonator only had a three minute delay... the bomb could go off any second.
Come on, Garak.

quote: Good morning.
Morning.
What are you smiling at?
I was just thinking... if we hadn't had our little talk the other day, we'd both be standing here staring at our shoes.
Not a chance. I'd have turned and walked the other way as soon as I saw you.
I'm glad we put all that behind us.
Me too.
I guess they worked it out...
It always brings a tear to my eye to see a Nagus pass his staff to a successor. It's a privilege to witness this historic moment.
Just wait and see. It's going to be more historic than you think.
They're here!
There you are, my boy! I have something for you.
Not so fast, Zek. We need to talk.
I knew you were going to make this difficult.
My mind is made up, Quark. Whining and complaining won't change anything.
I won't have any part of what you're doing to our once proud civilization. A man can only be pushed so far. If you want me to be Nagus, you're going to have to let me do things my way.
Who wants you to be Nagus?
Out of the way, Quark.
Congratulations, Rom. You're going to make a fine Nagus.
I am... ?
What's the matter? You seemed so happy when I talked to you the other day.
I did... ?
That was me!
You? Oh. I thought I was talking to Rom. It must've been all the static. Glad we cleared that up.
This is insane. You actually want Rom to be Nagus?
It was my idea.
Figures. He's an idiot.
You've always underestimated your brother.

A new Ferenginar needs a new kind of Nagus. A kinder, gentler Nagus. And that's you, my boy. (holding up the cane) It's a great responsibility to stand at the bow of the Ferengi ship of state... a Nagus has to navigate the waters of the great material continuum, avoid the shoals of bankruptcy and seek the strong winds of prosperity.
I'll do the best I can.
May I be the first to offer my congratulations!
Oh, Rom!
Way to go, Dad!
All right, fine! You want Rom? You can have him! In fact, you deserve him! He's perfect for this new worker's paradise of yours! He can save the environment and levy all the... taxes he wants!
He's not taking it very well.
As far as I'm concerned, the Ferenginar I knew doesn't exist anymore! No -- I take that back. It does exist. Right here in this bar.
This establishment will be the last outpost of what made Ferenginar great -- the unrelenting lust for profit. Broik -- water the drinks! M'Pella -- rig the dabo table!
Rom -- I want to buy the bar back.
That's all right, Brother, I'll give it to you.
I suppose you're going to let me keep the five thousand bars of latinum too.
You're my brother.
And you're an idiot, but I love you. Congratulations. You're the perfect Nagus for the new Ferenginar.
Are you sure we picked the right brother?
Come along, dear -- Risa's waiting.
You know, I could use a financial advisor.
No kidding. But it's not going to be me. This Ferengi belongs right here.
I know someone who's available...
Forget it.
Don't be so hasty. Let him give you a pedicure first. Now if you'll excuse me, I have to get to work. There's money to be made.

-- according to our intelligence reports, the Dominion has completely withdrawn from Klingon, Federation and Romulan space. They seem to be forming a new defense perimeter within Cardassian territory.
They must know we've developed a countermeasure against the Breen weapon.
That would be my guess.
There are advantages to falling back... they shorten their own supply lines while forcing us to lengthen ours.
And with a smaller perimeter to defend, they'll be less vulnerable to hit and run attacks. It would take a major offensive to break through their lines.
At a cost of thousands of ships. The wiser course would be to simply contain them within their perimeter.
That's what they're hoping we'll do -- so they'll have time to rebuild their forces.
He's right. We have them on the defensive -- we should attack with everything we've got.
Trying to break through that line will be a very ugly, very bloody job...
If we do nothing, the Dominion could sit behind that perimeter for the next five years rearming themselves. And when they're ready to come out... God help us all.
The Klingon Empire votes to hit them now -- before they have time to recover.
Considering the alternative... I'm afraid I have to concur.
Very well.
Then it's settled... we attack.
You're up late. Waiting for me?
What's wrong?
I'm pregnant.
Are you sure?
Of course I'm sure.
I didn't mean... it's just... a baby! You and me... wow. I hadn't even... a baby?
Surprise.
Surprise is right -- how did... ?
I think somebody forgot to get their injection last month...
And Julian even reminded me. But with everything that's been going on...
You don't have to apologize.
I'm not. Are you kidding? This is great!
I'm glad you think so.
But you don't?
I just keep thinking about... the Prophets. They warned you that marrying me would bring you sorrow.
We've been through this, Kas.
I know we have. We said we weren't going to let the Prophets run our lives. But that was before... this. What if they... were trying to warn you... that something's going to happen to our --
Shhh.
Nothing's going to happen to our baby.
How can you be sure?
Because I'm the Emissary of the Prophets and I know that everything's going to be okay.
I hope you're right...
We're having a baby...
We're having a baby...
A baby...
Wake up. It's time to go.
Hi, honey.
It's almost seven. Time to get ready.
Ready? Ready for what?
The picnic!
Was that today?
Yes! Don't you remember?
We'd better get going then.
I'm going to wear my blue jumper.
Good idea, honey.
I can't believe how much she's grown. She must be four inches taller than the last time I saw her.
And you must be five pounds heavier. What've you been eating while we've been gone?
The usual.
Well, say goodbye to the usual. I'm back and you're going to start eating right again.
Can it wait until after the picnic?
Would you help me put this on?
Of course, Honey.
Where's the sunscreen?
I already packed it.
This is where we're going, Yoshi. See?
Last time we went to Golana, you were inside Mommy's tummy.
We'd better get down to the airlock. The shuttle leaves in twenty minutes.
Can we bring Chester?
I don't think that's a good idea.
He might get lost.
On second thought.
All right, let's go.
Come on, Lupi.
No sausages?
I know what I'm going to be when I grow up.
You do?
Mm-hm. I'm going to be an exo- bologist.
An exo-bologist? What's that?
Someone who studies animals from other planets.
Like Chester....
Daddy, if you send us away again, can we take Chester?
Honey, I'm not going to send you away again.
You're not?
I only did it because it wasn't safe for you to be on the station.
I know.
From now on, we're going to stay together.
Promise?
Promise.
Want to see me do cartwheels?
You bet.
How are you, little fella?
I couldn't have said it better myself. (sighs contentedly, looks at Keiko) Real sunshine, fresh air... you and the kids. Life doesn't get any better.
That was a big promise you made.
I meant it.
I know. But what if the war heats up again and you decide the station isn't safe anymore?
I'll put in for a transfer. I'm not going to be apart from you ever again.
Molly?!
Molly? Molly!
Help!
Daddy!
Over here!
Molly!
Daddy!
Daddy!
Hold on, Molly. I'm coming.
Hold on!
Have you figured out what this thing is yet?
It's some sort of time portal. From the chroniton signature, we think it sent Molly about three hundred years into the past.
I wonder what this place was like three centuries ago...
Odo contacted the Bajoran Archaelogical Institute to see what he could find out.
How do we get Molly back?
First we have to find a way to reactivate the portal -- it's been abandoned for a long time and it destabilized when Molly fell through. The problem is, we're not sure how this technology works.
(looking over at O'Brien) Something tells me the chief isn't going to stop until he figures it out.
Something tells me you're right.
Assuming you can get it back on-line, then what?
We punch a transport scanning beam through the portal and try to lock on to Molly's DNA signature.
Then pull her back into the present.
That's the idea.
Bloody hell!
Shh. It's okay.
Maybe you should take him up to the Defiant. It's too cold in here for him.
I'm not going anywhere.
I'll take him.
It's all right, Yoshi. I'm going to get your sister back for you.
Give me a hand with this...
-- renay teli tah beh-soh... renay teli tah beh-soh, mo-zha ben'koh.
You're very good with him.
He knows me. I had him inside me for five months..
I think I'd like to have one of my own, someday...
According to the archaeologists I talked to, the portal was built by a civilization that vanished a thousand years ago.
Which means if Molly survived the fall, she would've found herself all alone.
You're saying the planet was uninhabited three hundred years ago?
The first Bajoran colonists didn't arrive until the turn of the century.
An eight year-old girl stranded alone on a deserted planet.
With any luck, the chief'll be able to beam her out a few minutes after she fell. She'll hardly know she was gone.
I'm scared, Miles. You've been at it for over a day. Tell me you're getting closer.
I think I've found a way to modulate the temporal field generators. If it works, Molly'll be home in a few hours.
She was so excited about coming here again... it's all she could talk about when I told her we were moving back to the station...
Our poor baby... where is she... what happened to her... ?
Shh. I'm going to get her back. Everything's going to be all right...
Dax to O'Brien.
Go ahead.
The power convertor you asked me to reconfigure... ? It's ready to go on-line.
What does that mean, Miles?
It means Molly's coming home.
Transporter interface link?

quote: There's no doubt about it. The DNA sequences match. This is definitely Molly.
My readings indicate she's about eighteen.
We pulled her out ten years too late.
It's a miracle you found a way to get her back at all.
If you tried again, maybe you could pull her out when she was still a little girl.
If you retrieve little Molly, there'd be no one to grow up and become this Molly. You'd be erasing her existence.
(trying to convince himself that it's still an option) But our Molly would be back.
This is our Molly. We may have missed ten years of her life, but we don't have the right to take them away from her.
She's been deprived of human contact for a long time. It's not going to be easy for her to re-assimilate.
Her language skills are going to be rusty. The two of you are the best hope we have of helping her recover them.
She didn't seem to remember us.
She was so scared I doubt she even saw what we looked like.
That's true, but don't expect her to accept you right away. It's possible that she blocked out the memories of her earlier life in order to cope with her isolation.
Just tell us what you want us to do.

I'm going to keep her sedated until we get back to Deep Space Nine. I've contacted Captain Sisko and told him we need to set up an environment where she'll feel safe. He's having one of the cargo bays converted. I want you there with her when she wakes up.
What happens then?
I'm afraid there aren't any rules in a case like this. We'll have to feel our way through the process...
-- and mister froggy goes... Wee!
Hi.
We have a visitor.
(to Yoshi; with mock sternness) And what exactly is this infant doing in my home?
I offered to watch him so the O'Briens could spend time with Molly.
I thought you said you were going to be working tonight.
I was going to do a spectral scan of that comet that's passing through the Denorias belt. But if I did that, who'd look after you?
Me.
That's all right. I want to stay with him.
Jadzia, you've been waiting for that comet to come into sensor range for weeks.
There'll be other comets.
Go. I will take care of Yoshi.
Worf... you're very sweet. But let's face it. You're not good with babies.
I raised Alexander.
That's different. He was four years old when he moved in with you. You never had to change his diapers. Babies are a handful. I should know. I had nine of them --
(he's heard it all before) I know. Five as a mother, four as a father. I can handle a fourteen-month old child.
I'm not saying you can't --
Fine. Go run your sensor scans.
You're not holding him right.
Leave us.
All right, all right. I'm leaving.
Hello, Molly. -
It's all right, Molly. We won't hurt you.
Would you like something to eat? I bet you're hungry.
Look at this. Golana melon.
Hmm, delicious.
Here... it's for you.
Good, isn't it?
Molly, do you remember me? It's Mommy.
Miles, what's she doing?
I think she's trying to figure out who we are. She probably remembers looking up at us when she was little.
That's right, Honey. It's Mommy and Daddy.
Show it to her.
I brought something for you.
It's Lupi. Remember how she used to sleep right next to you on your pillow every night? She's missed you, Molly.
Go on, take her.
Yes. That's right, it's Lupi. You remember now, don't you?
This is a ball, Molly.
